@MarkInTheMountains - Your use of the term "huge advantage" about constructors suggests you view a crossword puzzle as a contest between constructor and solver. 

I find this idea curious. It reminds me of comments that accuse a constructor of "showing off" or trying to prove they're "smarter than we are." 

It's always seemed to me constructors want to give solvers a fun challenge, but that they do indeed want their puzzles to be solved. I don't think most constructors think of what they do as a competition they're trying to win.

@MarkInTheMountains
saying something puts constructors "at a huge advantage" suggests that this is somehow a competition between constructors and solvers; I don't agree with that. They construct as a service to us (albeit also a labor of love for which they're paid a pittance), and we solve for our own pleasure, using rules of our own devising. If by using various tools they find fill using legitimate words that they didn't previously know, and especially if they can use them to replace OREO or EEL or EERIE or EMU, I'm all for it. Even if they didn't know the word, I might be familiar with it. And I trust them and the editors to try to make the crosses kind when the answers are relatively obscure.

And no, I'm not familiar with any particular name for the type of crossword you suggested. But I do think @SP's comment, as usual, is on point.

@MarkInTheMountains

I have trouble understanding how anything a constructor does can be construed as "cheating".  They can do anything they wish to in service of creating a good puzzle.
Now, we may disagree on what constitutes a "good puzzle", but that's another story.

@MarkInTheMountains

Interesting question and I don’t know the answer. I agree that constructors have a tough mission: Challenge me with my preexisting knowledge base. If they miss that sweet spot for some people you see the “not fun”, “too much trivia “, “unfair” or “lazy” comments come out. 

